"# Chapter 5 — Character Predicates

In Motoi, a character is a one-character string. That is a small
lie R7RS lets us tell — most Schemes have a distinct character type,
but the character LIBRARY works identically. `char-alphabetic?`,
`char-upcase`, `char->integer` — they all take a one-character string
and do the character-y thing.

## Why character predicates exist

Once you split a string into a list of characters (Chapter 4), you
often want to classify or transform each one. The character library
is how you say 'is this a letter?', 'is this a digit?', 'what does
this look like in uppercase?' one character at a time.

## Problem 1 — Test a character

`char-alphabetic?`, `char-numeric?`, `char-whitespace?` — the three
big classifications.

```
(display (char-alphabetic? \"a\"))
;; => #t
(display (char-alphabetic? \"5\"))
;; => #f
(display (char-numeric? \"5\"))
;; => #t
(display (char-whitespace? \" \"))
;; => #t
```

Fine-grained case tests:

```
(display (char-upper-case? \"A\"))
;; => #t
(display (char-lower-case? \"a\"))
;; => #t
(display (char-lower-case? \"A\"))
;; => #f
```

## Problem 2 — Transform a character's case

`char-upcase`, `char-downcase`, and `char-foldcase` all return a
new character.

```
(display (char-upcase \"a\"))
;; => \"A\"
(display (char-downcase \"Z\"))
;; => \"z\"
```

`char-foldcase` returns the CANONICAL folded form for
case-insensitive comparison. Usually that's the lowercase form:

```
(display (char-foldcase \"A\"))
;; => \"a\"
```

Use `char-foldcase` when you want to compare two characters
ignoring case: `(equal? (char-foldcase a) (char-foldcase b))`.

## Problem 3 — Convert between characters and integers

Every character has a codepoint — an integer that identifies it in
the underlying character set (ASCII for the printable low range,
Unicode for everything else).

```
(display (char->integer \"a\"))
;; => 97
(display (char->integer \"A\"))
;; => 65
(display (integer->char 65))
;; => \"A\"
```

The delta between uppercase and lowercase in ASCII is exactly 32:

```
(display (- (char->integer \"a\") (char->integer \"A\")))
;; => 32
```

That is why you sometimes see `(- codepoint 32)` in old C code.
Motoi's `char-upcase` handles this correctly across the whole
alphabet without you having to remember it.

`digit-value` is a convenience: given a character-that-looks-like-a-digit,
return the integer value.

```
(display (digit-value \"7\"))
;; => 7
```

## Problem 4 (expert) — Count vowels in a string

Compose the string library with the character library.

```
(define (vowel? c)
  (member (char-foldcase c) (list \"a\" \"e\" \"i\" \"o\" \"u\")))

(define (count-vowels s)
  (length (filter vowel? (string->list s))))

(display (count-vowels \"hello world\"))
;; => 3
(display (count-vowels \"MOTOI\"))
;; => 3
```

Read the shape: `string->list` breaks the string into a list of
one-character strings; `filter vowel?` keeps only the vowels;
`length` counts what's left. `char-foldcase` normalizes so both
lowercase and uppercase vowels get counted.

## Problem 5 — A simple check-digit validator

Verify that a phone number contains only digits and formatting.

```
(define (only-digits-and-dashes? s)
  (for-each-truthy?
    (lambda (c)
      (or (char-numeric? c)
          (equal? c \"-\")
          (equal? c \" \")))
    (string->list s)))

(define (for-each-truthy? pred lst)
  (cond ((null? lst) #t)
        ((pred (car lst)) (for-each-truthy? pred (cdr lst)))
        (else #f)))

(display (only-digits-and-dashes? \"555-1234\"))
;; => #t
(display (only-digits-and-dashes? \"555-CATS\"))
;; => #f
```

Notice: `only-digits-and-dashes?` doesn't just check whether ANY
character is bad — it fails as soon as one is bad. That is the
shape of a validator.

## Capstone — Title-case a sentence by hand

The string library has `string-titlecase`, but you can build one
using only the character library and higher-order verbs. This is
the kind of exercise that makes character predicates click.

```
(define (words-in s)
  (string-split s))

(define (capitalize-word w)
  (if (= (string-length w) 0)
      w
      (string-append
        (char-upcase (string-take w 1))
        (string-downcase (string-drop w 1)))))

(define (titlecase-manually s)
  (string-join (map capitalize-word (words-in s)) \" \"))

(display (titlecase-manually \"the quick brown fox\"))
;; => \"The Quick Brown Fox\"
```

The chain reads: split into words, capitalize each, rejoin with
spaces. `capitalize-word` upcases the first character and downcases
the rest.

## Alphabet of the character library

- **Test:** `char?`, `char-alphabetic?`, `char-numeric?`,
  `char-whitespace?`, `char-upper-case?`, `char-lower-case?`
- **Compare:** `char=?`, `char<?`, `char>?`, `char<=?`, `char>=?`
- **Transform:** `char-upcase`, `char-downcase`, `char-foldcase`
- **Convert:** `char->integer`, `integer->char`, `digit-value`

Twenty verbs, one family, and they compose cleanly with the string
library from Chapter 4.

## What's next

In Chapter 6 we go BELOW characters — to raw bytes. Bytevectors are
what you reach for when you need to talk to code that thinks in
bytes: file I/O, network protocols, cryptography, image formats.
")
